<br>
<!--EZCODE IMAGE START--><img src="http://www.angelfire.com/art/foxfire/banner1.jpg"><!--EZCODE IMAGE END--> </font><P><P><i></i></TD></TR><TR BGCOLOR=#CCCCCC><TD NOWRAP width=20% valign=top align=left><B><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=2><A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/uaztech.showPublicProfile?language=EN>AzTech</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC=http://omu.kuiki.net/az.gif BORDER=0 HEIGHT=10 WIDTH=10></FONT></B><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>OMU Faculty</FONT><BR><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>(</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#1B1B37>4/11/01</FONT> <FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1 COLOR=#1B1B37>9:48:09 am</FONT><FONT FACE="Verdana,Arial" SIZE=1>)<BR></FONT><BR><img src=http://omu.kuiki.net/aztech.jpg WIDTH=60 HEIGHT=60></TD><TD VALIGN=TOP ALIGN=LEFT><B><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">Re: Inking Q...</font></B><HR><FONT SIZE=2 FACE="Verdana,Arial">When I'm doing commision work, I use nibs.  C-5 and C-6 work well for me, as do Hunt 102 and 107 for fine detail work.  I use technical pens for static lines, like buildings and such.  They tend to work better for me when I'm using a ruler.  I use brushes when inking larger pieces (like in the 18&quot; x 24&quot; range), and to fill in those huge areas of black when inking space scenes.<br>
<br>
When I ink for fun (as in if no one is gonna buy it), I use whatever I can get my grubby little fingers on.  I'm using a plain old tube-marker to ink the panelwork in the Fight Club.  Nylon-tipped pens are fine, as they can provide varying width of line by applying more pressure.<br>
<br>
Bottom line:  Use what suits you best!  You won't know what works best for you until you try several methods, and settle into your niche.</font><P><p><b>"AGAAAIIIN!!!   FROM THE TAAAHHHP!!!"</b></p>
